and","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hundon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Caitlin, Dermot, Liam.","English: habitational name from Dundon in Somerset, named from Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ + <i>denu</i> ‘valley’.","Irish (Munster): perhaps a variant of the Norman surname   Dando  , although the additional final <i>-n</i> is difficult to explain."],"variants":[{"name":"Dando","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from Aunou-le-Faucon in Orne, Normandy, with fused preposition. Aunou was named for an alder grove, from Latin <i>alnus</i> ‘alder’ + the Gaulish suffix <i>-avum</i>. In medieval England <i>d'Aunou</i> developed an intrusive <i>-d-</i>, giving <i>Dando</i>. The surname was sometimes confused with <i>d'Aunay</i> or <i>d'Auney</i> (see   Delaney  )."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":22,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Hundon was born in 1360, in England. He had at least 1 daughter. He died in 1385, in Lincolnshire, England, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1360–1385":"1360–1385","1385–1426":"1385–1426","1426":"1426","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1360–1385":"1360–1385","1385–1426":"1385–1426","1426":"1426","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"1360–1385":"1360–1385","1385–1426":"1385–1426","1426":"1426","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","England":"Angleterre","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Hundon est né en 1360, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé en 1385, à Lincolnshire, Angleterre, à l’âge de 25 ans."},"de":{"1360–1385":"1360–1385","1385–1426":"1385–1426","1426":"1426","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Hundon wurde 1360 in England geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Tochter. Er starb 1385 im Alter von 25 Jahren in Lincolnshire, England."},"ht":{"1360–1385":"1360–1385","1385–1426":"1385–1426","1426":"1426","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"hu":{"1360–1385":"1360–1385","1385–1426":"1385–1426","1426":"1426","1385":"1385","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","England":"England","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"id":{"1360–1385":"1360–1385","1385–1426":"1385–142